# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ascomycota
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:ascomycota/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:ascomycota/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:ascomycota/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:ascomycota/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:ascomycota/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:ascomycota/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:ascomycota/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:ascomycota/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The **human immunodeficiency virus** (HIV) is a retrovirus that attacks the immune system.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Without treatment, it can lead to a spectrum of conditions including **acquired immunodeficiency syndrome** (AIDS).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It can be managed with treatment and become a manageable chronic health condition.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] While there is no cure or vaccine for HIV, antiretroviral treatment can slow the course of the disease, and, if used before significant disease progression, can extend the life expectancy of someone living with HIV to a nearly standard level.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] An HIV-positive person on treatment can expect to live a normal life, and die with the virus, not of it.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Effective treatment for HIV-positive people (people living with HIV) involves a life-long regimen of medicine to suppress the virus, making the viral load undetectable.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Early testing can show if treatment is needed to stop progression and to prevent infecting others.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Treatment is recommended as soon as the diagnosis is made.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] An HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Campaigns by UNAIDS and other organizations around the world have communicated this as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Without treatment the infection can interfere with the immune system, and eventually progress to AIDS, sometimes taking many years.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Following initial infection an individual may not notice any symptoms, or may experience a brief period of influenza-like illness.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] During this period the person may not know that they are HIV-positive, yet they will be able to pass on the virus.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Typically, this period is followed by a prolonged incubation period with no symptoms.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Eventually the HIV infection increases the risk of developing other infections such as tuberculosis, as well as other opportunistic infections, and tumors which are rare in people who have normal immune function.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The late stage is often also associated with unintended weight loss.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Without treatment, the life expectancy of an individual with HIV is around 11 years.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV is spread primarily by unprotected sex (including anal, oral and vaginal sex), contaminated hypodermic needles or blood transfusions, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Some bodily fluids, such as saliva, sweat, and tears, do not transmit the virus.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Oral sex has little risk of transmitting the virus.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Ways to avoid catching HIV and preventing the spread include safe sex, treatment to prevent infection ("PrEP"), treatment to stop infection in someone who has been recently exposed ("PEP"), treating those who are infected, and needle exchange programs.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Disease in a baby can often be prevented by giving both the mother and child antiretroviral medication.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Recognized worldwide in the early 1980s, HIV/AIDS has had a large impact on society, both as an illness and as a source of discrimination.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The disease also has large economic impacts.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There are many misconceptions about HIV/AIDS, such as the belief that it can be transmitted by casual non-sexual contact.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The disease has become subject to many controversies involving religion, including the Catholic Church's position not to support condom use as prevention.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It has attracted international medical and political attention as well as large-scale funding since it was identified in the 1980s.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV made the jump from other primates to humans in west-central Africa in the early-to-mid-20th century.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 1981 and its cause—HIV infection—was identified in the early part of the decade.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Between the first time AIDS was readily identified through 2024, the disease is estimated to have caused at least 42.3 million deaths worldwide.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In 2025, 1.2 million people acquired HIV and an estimated 40.9 million people worldwide were living with HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a pandemic—a disease outbreak which is present over a large area and is actively spreading.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The United States' National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the Gates Foundation have pledged $200 million focused on developing a global cure for AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There are three main stages of HIV infection: acute infection, clinical latency, and AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The initial period following infection with HIV is called acute HIV, primary HIV or acute retroviral syndrome.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Many individuals develop an influenza-like illness, mononucleosis or glandular fever 2–4 weeks after exposure while others have no significant symptoms.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Symptoms occur in 40–90% of cases and most commonly include fever, large tender lymph nodes, throat inflammation, a rash, headache, tiredness, and/or sores of the mouth and genitals.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The rash, which occurs in 20–50% of cases, presents itself on the trunk and is maculopapular, classically.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Some people also develop opportunistic infections at this stage.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Gastrointestinal symptoms, such as vomiting or diarrhea may occur.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Neurological symptoms of peripheral neuropathy or Guillain–Barré syndrome also occur.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The duration of the symptoms varies, but is usually one or two weeks.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] These symptoms are not often recognized as signs of HIV infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Family doctors or hospitals can misdiagnose cases as one of the many common infectious diseases with similar symptoms.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Someone with an unexplained fever who may have been recently exposed to HIV should consider testing to find out if they have been infected.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The initial symptoms are followed by a stage called clinical latency, asymptomatic HIV, or chronic HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Without treatment, this second stage of the natural history of HIV infection can last from about three years to over 20 years (on average, about eight years).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] While typically there are few or no symptoms at first, near the end of this stage many people experience fever, weight loss, gastrointestinal problems and muscle pains.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Between 50% and 70% of people also develop persistent generalized lymphadenopathy, characterized by unexplained, non-painful enlargement of more than one group of lymph nodes (other than in the groin) for over three to six months.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Although most HIV-1 infected individuals have a detectable viral load and in the absence of treatment will eventually progress to AIDS, a small proportion (about 5%) retain high levels of CD4+ T cells (T helper cells) without antiretroviral therapy for more than five years.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] These individuals are classified as "HIV controllers" or long-term nonprogressors (LTNP).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Another group consists of those who maintain a low or undetectable viral load without anti-retroviral treatment, known as "elite controllers" or "elite suppressors".
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] They represent approximately 1 in 300 infected persons.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) is defined as an HIV infection with either a CD4+ T cell count below 200 cells per microlitre (μL) of blood or the occurrence of specific diseases associated with HIV infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In the absence of specific treatment, around half of people infected with HIV develop AIDS within ten years.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The most common initial conditions that alert to the presence of AIDS are pneumocystis pneumonia (40%), cachexia in the form of HIV wasting syndrome (20%), and esophageal candidiasis.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Other common signs include recurrent respiratory tract infections.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Opportunistic infections may be caused by bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites that are normally controlled by the immune system.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Which infections occur depends partly on what organisms are common in the person's environment.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] These infections may affect nearly every organ system.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] People with AIDS have an increased risk of developing various viral-induced cancers, including Kaposi's sarcoma, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Kaposi's sarcoma is the most common cancer, occurring in 10% to 20% of people with HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The second-most common cancer is lymphoma, which is the cause of death of nearly 16% of people with AIDS and is the initial sign of AIDS in 3% to 4%.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Both these cancers are associated with human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Cervical cancer occurs more frequently in those with AIDS because of its association with human papillomavirus (HPV).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Conjunctival cancer (of the layer that lines the inner part of eyelids and the white part of the eye) is also more common in those with HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Additionally, people with AIDS frequently have systemic symptoms such as prolonged fevers, sweats (particularly at night), swollen lymph nodes, chills, weakness, and unintended weight loss.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Diarrhea is another common symptom, present in about 90% of people with AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] They can also be affected by diverse psychiatric and neurological symptoms independent of opportunistic infections and cancers.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV is spread by three main routes: sexual contact, significant exposure to infected body fluids or tissues, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding (known as vertical transmission).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There is no risk of acquiring HIV if exposed to feces, nasal secretions, saliva, sputum, sweat, tears, urine, or vomit unless these are contaminated with blood.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is also possible to be co-infected by more than one strain of HIV—a condition known as HIV superinfection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The most frequent mode of transmission of HIV is through sexual contact with an infected person.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] However, an HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually, known as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The existence of functionally noncontagious HIV-positive people on antiretroviral therapy was controversially publicized in the 2008 Swiss Statement, and has since become accepted as medically sound.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Globally, the most common mode of HIV transmission is via sexual contacts between people of the opposite sex; however, the pattern of transmission varies among countries.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] As of 2017, most HIV transmission in the United States occurred among men who had sex with men (82% of new HIV diagnoses among males aged 13 and older and 70% of total new diagnoses).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In the US, gay and bisexual men aged 13 to 24 accounted for an estimated 92% of new HIV diagnoses among all men in their age group and 27% of new diagnoses among all gay and bisexual men.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] With regard to unprotected heterosexual contacts, estimates of the risk of HIV transmission per sexual act appear to be four to ten times higher in low-income countries than in high-income countries.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The risk of transmission from anal intercourse is especially high, estimated as 1.4–1.7% per act in both heterosexual and homosexual contacts.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] While the risk of transmission from oral sex is relatively low, it is still present.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The risk from receiving oral sex has been described as "nearly nil"; however, a few cases have been reported.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The per-act risk is estimated at 0–0.04% for receptive oral intercourse.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In settings involving prostitution in low-income countries, risk of female-to-male transmission has been estimated as 2.4% per act, and of male-to-female transmission as 0.05% per act.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Risk of transmission increases in the presence of many sexually transmitted infections and genital ulcers.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Genital ulcers increase the risk approximately fivefold.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Other sexually transmitted infections, such as gonorrhea, chlamydia, trichomoniasis, and bacterial vaginosis, are associated with somewhat smaller increases in risk of transmission.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The viral load of an infected person is an important risk factor in both sexual and mother-to-child transmission.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] During the first 2.5 months of an HIV infection, a person's infectiousness is twelve times higher due to the high viral load associated with acute HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] If the person is in the late stages of infection, rates of transmission are approximately eightfold greater.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Commercial sex workers (including those in pornography) have an increased likelihood of contracting HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Rough sex can be a factor associated with an increased risk of transmission.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Sexual assault is also believed to carry an increased risk of HIV transmission, as condoms are rarely worn, physical trauma to the vagina or rectum is likely, and there may be a greater risk of concurrent sexually transmitted infections.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The second-most frequent mode of HIV transmission is via blood and blood products.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Blood-borne transmission can be through needle-sharing during intravenous drug use, needle-stick injury, transfusion of contaminated blood or blood product, or medical injections with unsterilized equipment.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The risk from sharing a needle during drug injection is between 0.63% and 2.4% per act, with an average of 0.8%.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The risk of acquiring HIV from a needle stick from an HIV-infected person is estimated as 0.3% (about 1 in 333) per act and the risk following mucous membrane exposure to infected blood as 0.09% (about 1 in 1000) per act.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This risk may, however, be up to 5% if the introduced blood was from a person with a high viral load and the cut was deep.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In the United States, intravenous drug users made up 12% of all new cases of HIV in 2009, and in some areas more than 80% of people who inject drugs are predicted to be HIV-positive.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV is transmitted in about 90% of blood transfusions using infected blood.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In low-income countries, only half of transfusions may be appropriately screened (as of 2008), and it is estimated that up to 15% of HIV infections in these areas come from transfusion of infected blood and blood products, representing between 5% and 10% of global infections.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is possible to acquire HIV from organ and tissue transplantation, although this is rare because of screening.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Unsafe medical injections play a role in HIV spread in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In 2007, between 12% and 17% of infections in this region were attributed to medical syringe use.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The World Health Organization estimates the risk of transmission as a result of a medical injection in Africa at 1.2%.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Risks are also associated with invasive procedures, assisted delivery, and dental care in this area of the world.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] People giving or receiving tattoos, piercings, and scarification are theoretically at risk of infection but no confirmed cases have been documented.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is not possible for mosquitoes or other insects to transmit HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV can be transmitted from mother to child during pregnancy, during delivery, or through breast milk, resulting in the baby also contracting HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] As of 2008, vertical transmission accounted for about 90% of cases of HIV in children.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In the absence of treatment, the risk of transmission before or during birth is around 20%, and in those who also breastfeed 35%.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Treatment decreases this risk to less than 5%.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Antiretrovirals when taken by either the mother or the baby decrease the risk of transmission in those who do breastfeed.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] If blood contaminates food during pre-chewing it may pose a risk of transmission.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] If a woman is untreated, two years of breastfeeding results in an HIV/AIDS risk in her baby of about 17%.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Due to the increased risk of death without breastfeeding in many areas in the developing world, the World Health Organization recommends either exclusive breastfeeding or the provision of safe formula.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] All women known to be HIV-positive should be taking lifelong antiretroviral therapy.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV is the cause of the spectrum of disease known as HIV/AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV is a retrovirus that primarily infects components of the human immune system such as CD4+ T cells, macrophages and dendritic cells.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It directly and indirectly destroys CD4+ T cells.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV is a member of the genus *Lentivirus*, part of the family *Retroviridae*.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Lentiviruses share many morphological and biological characteristics.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Many species of mammals are infected by lentiviruses, which are characteristically responsible for long-duration illnesses with a long incubation period.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Lentiviruses are transmitted as single-stranded, positive-sense, enveloped RNA viruses.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Upon entry into the target cell, the viral RNA genome is converted (reverse transcribed) into double-stranded DNA by a virally encoded reverse transcriptase that is transported along with the viral genome in the virus particle.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The resulting viral DNA is then imported into the cell nucleus and integrated into the cellular DNA by a virally encoded integrase and host co-factors.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Once integrated, the virus may become latent, allowing the virus and its host cell to avoid detection by the immune system.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Alternatively, the virus may be transcribed, producing new RNA genomes and viral proteins that are packaged and released from the cell as new virus particles that begin the replication cycle anew.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV is now known to spread between CD4+ T cells by two parallel routes: cell-free spread and cell-to-cell spread, i.e. it employs hybrid spreading mechanisms.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In the cell-free spread, virus particles bud from an infected T cell, enter the blood/extracellular fluid and then infect another T cell following a chance encounter.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV can also disseminate by direct transmission from one cell to another by a process of cell-to-cell spread.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The hybrid spreading mechanisms of HIV contribute to the virus' ongoing replication against antiretroviral therapies.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Two types of HIV have been characterized: HIV-1 and HIV-2.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV-1 is the virus that was originally discovered (and initially referred to also as LAV or HTLV-III).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is more virulent, more infective, and is the cause of the majority of HIV infections globally.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The lower infectivity of HIV-2 as compared with HIV-1 implies that fewer people exposed to HIV-2 will be infected per exposure.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Because of its relatively poor capacity for transmission, HIV-2 is largely confined to West Africa.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] After the virus enters the body, there is a period of rapid viral replication, leading to an abundance of virus in the peripheral blood.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] During primary infection, the level of HIV may reach several million virus particles per milliliter of blood.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This response is accompanied by a marked drop in the number of circulating CD4+ T cells.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The acute viremia is almost invariably associated with activation of CD8+ T cells, which kill HIV-infected cells, and subsequently with antibody production, or seroconversion.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The CD8+ T cell response is thought to be important in controlling virus levels, which peak and then decline, as the CD4+ T cell counts recover.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] A good CD8+ T cell response has been linked to slower disease progression and a better prognosis, though it does not eliminate the virus.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Ultimately, HIV causes AIDS by depleting CD4+ T cells.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This weakens the immune system and allows opportunistic infections.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] T cells are essential to the immune response and without them, the body cannot fight infections or kill cancerous cells.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The mechanism of CD4+ T cell depletion differs in the acute and chronic phases.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] During the acute phase, HIV-induced cell lysis and killing of infected cells by CD8+ T cells accounts for CD4+ T cell depletion, although apoptosis may also be a factor.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] During the chronic phase, the consequences of generalized immune activation coupled with the gradual loss of the ability of the immune system to generate new T cells appear to account for the slow decline in CD4+ T cell numbers.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Although the symptoms of immune deficiency characteristic of AIDS do not appear for years after a person is infected, the bulk of CD4+ T cell loss occurs during the first weeks of infection, especially in the intestinal mucosa, which harbors the majority of the lymphocytes found in the body.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The reason for the preferential loss of mucosal CD4+ T cells is that the majority of mucosal CD4+ T cells express the CCR5 protein which HIV uses as a co-receptor to gain access to the cells, whereas only a small fraction of CD4+ T cells in the bloodstream do so.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] A specific genetic change that alters the CCR5 protein when present in both chromosomes very effectively prevents HIV-1 infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV seeks out and destroys CCR5 expressing CD4+ T cells during acute infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] A vigorous immune response eventually controls the infection and initiates the clinically latent phase.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] CD4+ T cells in mucosal tissues remain particularly affected.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Continuous HIV replication causes a state of generalized immune activation persisting throughout the chronic phase.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Immune activation, which is reflected by the increased activation state of immune cells and release of pro-inflammatory cytokines, results from the activity of several HIV gene products and the immune response to ongoing HIV replication.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is also linked to the breakdown of the immune surveillance system of the gastrointestinal mucosal barrier caused by the depletion of mucosal CD4+ T cells during the acute phase of disease.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS related eye diseases are common among people living with this disease worldwide.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Among these diseases, HIV retinopathy is the most common condition.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This condition is seen in 40% to 60% of HIV positive patients.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is also the most common cause of loss of vision in these patients.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is diagnosed via laboratory testing and then staged based on the presence of certain signs or symptoms.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV screening is recommended by the United States Preventive Services Task Force for all people 15 years to 65 years of age, including all pregnant women.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Additionally, testing is recommended for those at high risk, which includes anyone diagnosed with a sexually transmitted illness.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In many areas of the world, a third of HIV carriers only discover they are infected at an advanced stage of the disease when AIDS or severe immunodeficiency has become apparent.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Most people infected with HIV develop seroconverted (antigen-specific) antibodies within three to twelve weeks after the initial infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Diagnosis of primary HIV before seroconversion is done by measuring HIV-RNA or p24 antigen.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Positive results obtained by antibody or PCR testing are confirmed either by a different antibody or by PCR.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Antibody tests in children younger than 18 months are typically inaccurate, due to the continued presence of maternal antibodies.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Thus HIV infection can only be diagnosed by PCR testing for HIV RNA or DNA, or via testing for the p24 antigen.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Much of the world lacks access to reliable PCR testing, and people in many places simply wait until either symptoms develop or the child is old enough for accurate antibody testing.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In sub-Saharan Africa between 2007 and 2009, between 30% and 70% of the population were aware of their HIV status.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In 2009, between 3.6% and 42% of men and women in sub-Saharan countries were tested; this represented a significant increase compared to previous years.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Two main clinical staging systems are used to classify HIV and HIV-related disease for surveillance purposes: the WHO disease staging system for HIV infection and disease, and the CDC classification system for HIV infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The CDC's classification system is more frequently adopted in developed countries.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Since the WHO's staging system does not require laboratory tests, it is suited to the resource-restricted conditions encountered in developing countries, where it can also be used to help guide clinical management.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Despite their differences, the two systems allow a comparison for statistical purposes.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The World Health Organization first proposed a definition for AIDS in 1986.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Since then, the WHO classification has been updated and expanded several times, with the most recent version being published in 2007.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also created a classification system for HIV, and updated it in 2008 and 2014.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This system classifies HIV infections based on CD4 count and clinical symptoms, and describes the infection in five groups.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] For surveillance purposes, the AIDS diagnosis still stands even if, after treatment, the CD4+ T cell count rises to above 200 per μL of blood or other AIDS-defining illnesses are cured.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Consistent condom use reduces the risk of HIV transmission by approximately 80% over the long term.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] When condoms are used consistently by a couple in which one person is infected, the rate of HIV infection is less than 1% per year.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There is some evidence to suggest that female condoms may provide an equivalent level of protection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Application of a vaginal gel containing tenofovir (a reverse transcriptase inhibitor) immediately before sex seems to reduce infection rates by approximately 40% among African women.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] By contrast, use of the spermicide nonoxynol-9 may increase the risk of transmission due to its tendency to cause vaginal and rectal irritation.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Circumcision in sub-Saharan Africa "reduces the acquisition of HIV by heterosexual men by between 38% and 66% over 24 months".
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Owing to these studies, both the World Health Organization and UNAIDS recommended male circumcision in 2007 as a method of preventing female-to-male HIV transmission in areas with high rates of HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] However, whether it protects against male-to-female transmission is disputed, and whether it is of benefit in developed countries and among men who have sex with men is undetermined.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Programs encouraging sexual abstinence do not appear to affect subsequent HIV risk.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Evidence of any benefit from peer education is equally poor.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Comprehensive sexual education provided at school may decrease high-risk behavior.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] A substantial minority of young people continues to engage in high-risk practices despite knowing about HIV/AIDS, underestimating their own risk of becoming infected with HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Voluntary counseling and testing people for HIV does not affect risky behavior in those who test negative but does increase condom use in those who test positive.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Enhanced family planning services appear to increase the likelihood of women with HIV using contraception, compared to basic services.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is not known whether treating other sexually transmitted infections is effective in preventing HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Antiretroviral treatment among people with HIV whose CD4 count ≤ 550 cells/μL is a very effective way to prevent HIV infection of their partner (a strategy known as treatment as prevention, or TASP).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] TASP is associated with a 10- to 20-fold reduction in transmission risk.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Pre-exposure prophylaxis for HIV ("PrEP") with a daily dose of the medications tenofovir, with or without emtricitabine, is effective in people at high risk including men who have sex with men, couples where one is HIV-positive, and young heterosexuals in Africa.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It may also be effective in intravenous drug users, with a study finding a decrease in risk of 0.7 to 0.4 per 100 person years.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The USPSTF, in 2019, recommended PrEP in those who are at high risk.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Universal precautions within the health care environment are believed to be effective in decreasing the risk of HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Intravenous drug use is an important risk factor, and harm reduction strategies such as needle-exchange programs and opioid substitution therapy appear effective in decreasing this risk.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] A course of antiretrovirals administered within 48 to 72 hours after exposure to HIV-positive blood or genital secretions is referred to as post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The use of the single agent zidovudine reduces the risk of an HIV infection five-fold following a needle-stick injury.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] As of 2013, the prevention regimen recommended in the United States consists of three medications—tenofovir, emtricitabine and raltegravir—as this may reduce the risk further.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] PEP treatment is recommended after a sexual assault when the perpetrator is known to be HIV-positive, but is controversial when their HIV status is unknown.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The duration of treatment is usually four weeks and is frequently associated with adverse effects—where zidovudine is used, about 70% of cases result in adverse effects such as nausea (24%), fatigue (22%), emotional distress (13%) and headaches (9%).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Programs to prevent the vertical transmission of HIV (from mothers to children) can reduce rates of transmission by 92–99%.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This primarily involves the use of a combination of antiviral medications during pregnancy and after birth in the infant, and potentially includes bottle feeding rather than breastfeeding.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] If replacement feeding is acceptable, feasible, affordable, sustainable and safe, mothers should avoid breastfeeding their infants; however, exclusive breastfeeding is recommended during the first months of life if this is not the case.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] If exclusive breastfeeding is carried out, the provision of extended antiretroviral prophylaxis to the infant decreases the risk of transmission.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In 2015, Cuba became the first country in the world to eradicate mother-to-child transmission of HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Currently there is no licensed vaccine for HIV or AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The most effective vaccine trial to date, RV 144, was published in 2009; it found a partial reduction in the risk of transmission of roughly 30%, stimulating some hope in the research community of developing a truly effective vaccine.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is a chronic condition, as there is currently no cure.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Treatment consists of highly active antiretroviral therapy (ART), which slows progression of the disease.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] As of 2025, 40.9 million people globally were living with HIV, and 32.1 million people were accessing ART.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Treatment also includes preventive and active treatment of opportunistic infections.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] As of July 2022, four people have been successfully cleared of HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Rapid initiation of antiretroviral therapy within one week of diagnosis appear to improve treatment outcomes in low and medium-income settings and is recommend for newly diagnosed HIV patients.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV retinopathy was a very common cause of blindness in people with AIDS before the introduction of highly active antiretroviral therapy, but its incidence is declining due to proper and timely management of AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Even if there are signs of retinopathy, it may reverse as CD4+ T cell counts increase.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Reversal of HIV retinopathy is a helpful sign of positive response to antiretroviral therapy in AIDS patients.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] But if HIV treatment is delayed it may lead to permanent visual loss.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Occurrence of HIV retinopathy may also be an indicator of therapeutic failure in AIDS patients undergoing treatment.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Current ART options are combinations (or "cocktails") consisting of at least three medications belonging to at least two types, or "classes", of antiretroviral agents.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There are also two drugs, ritonavir (RTV) and cobicistat (COBI) which can be used as pharmacokinetic (PK) enhancers (or boosters) to improve the PK profiles of PIs and the INSTI elvitegravir (EVG).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The World Health Organization and the United States recommend antiretrovirals in people of all ages (including pregnant women) as soon as the diagnosis is made, regardless of CD4 count.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Once treatment is begun, it is recommended that it is continued without breaks or "holidays".
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Many people are diagnosed only after treatment ideally should have begun.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The desired outcome of treatment is a long-term plasma HIV-RNA count below 50 copies/mL.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Levels to determine if treatment is effective are initially recommended after four weeks and once levels fall below 50 copies/mL checks every three to six months are typically adequate.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Inadequate control is deemed to be greater than 400 copies/mL.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Based on these criteria treatment is effective in more than 95% of people during the first year.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Benefits of treatment include a decreased risk of progression to AIDS and a decreased risk of death.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In the developing world, treatment also improves physical and mental health.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] With treatment, there is a 70% reduced risk of acquiring tuberculosis.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Additional benefits include a decreased risk of transmission of the disease to sexual partners and a decrease in mother-to-child transmission.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The effectiveness of treatment depends to a large part on compliance.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Reasons for non-adherence to treatment include poor access to medical care, inadequate social supports, mental illness and drug abuse.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The complexity of treatment regimens (due to pill numbers and dosing frequency) and adverse effects may reduce adherence.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Even though cost is an important issue with some medications, 47% of those who needed them were taking them in low- and middle-income countries as of 2010, and the rate of adherence is similar in low-income and high-income countries.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Specific adverse events are related to the antiretroviral agent taken.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Some relatively common adverse events include: lipodystrophy syndrome, dyslipidemia, and diabetes mellitus, especially with protease inhibitors.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Other common symptoms include diarrhea, and an increased risk of cardiovascular disease.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Newer recommended treatments are associated with fewer adverse effects.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Certain medications may be associated with birth defects and therefore may be unsuitable for women hoping to have children.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Treatment recommendations for children are somewhat different from those for adults.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The World Health Organization recommends treating all children less than five years of age; children above five are treated like adults.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The United States guidelines recommend treating all children less than 12 months of age and all those with HIV RNA counts greater than 100,000 copies/mL between one year and five years of age.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In 2020, the European Medicines Agency recommended approval of a long-acting injectable combination of the antiretrovirals rilpivirine and cabotegravir, marketed as Rekambys and Vocabria; unlike standard daily pills, it is administered by intramuscular injection every one to two months.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is indicated as maintenance therapy for adults who are already virologically suppressed (viral load below 50 copies/mL) on a stable regimen, with no documented resistance to non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors or integrase strand transfer inhibitors.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Measures to prevent opportunistic infections are effective in many people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In addition to improving current disease, treatment with antiretrovirals reduces the risk of developing additional opportunistic infections.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Adults and adolescents who are living with HIV (even on anti-retroviral therapy) with no evidence of active tuberculosis in settings with high tuberculosis burden should receive isoniazid preventive therapy (IPT); the tuberculin skin test can be used to help decide if IPT is needed.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Children with HIV may benefit from screening for tuberculosis.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Vaccination against hepatitis A and B is advised for all people at risk of HIV before they become infected; however, it may also be given after infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole prophylaxis between four and six weeks of age, and ceasing breastfeeding of infants born to HIV-positive mothers, is recommended in resource-limited settings.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] It is also recommended to prevent PCP when a person's CD4 count is below 200 cells/uL and in those who have or have previously had PCP.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] People with substantial immunosuppression are also advised to receive prophylactic therapy for toxoplasmosis and MAC.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Appropriate preventive measures reduced the rate of these infections by 50% between 1992 and 1997.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Influenza vaccination and pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine are often recommended in people with HIV/AIDS with some evidence of benefit.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) has issued recommendations regarding nutrient requirements in HIV/AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Dietary intake of micronutrients at RDA levels by HIV-infected adults is recommended by the WHO; higher intake of vitamin A, zinc, and iron can produce adverse effects in HIV-positive adults, and is not recommended unless there is documented deficiency.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Dietary supplementation for people who are infected with HIV and who have inadequate nutrition or dietary deficiencies may strengthen their immune systems or help them recover from infections; however, evidence indicating an overall benefit in morbidity or reduction in mortality is not consistent.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] People with HIV/AIDS are up to four times more likely to develop type 2 diabetes than those who are not tested positive with the virus.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Evidence for supplementation with selenium is mixed with some tentative evidence of benefit.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] For pregnant and lactating women with HIV, multivitamin supplement improves outcomes for both mothers and children.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] If the pregnant or lactating mother has been advised to take anti-retroviral medication to prevent mother-to-child HIV transmission, multivitamin supplements should not replace these treatments.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There is some evidence that vitamin A supplementation in children with an HIV infection reduces mortality and improves growth.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In the US, approximately 60% of people with HIV use various forms of complementary or alternative medicine, whose effectiveness has not been established.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There is not enough evidence to support the use of herbal medicines.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There is insufficient evidence to recommend or support the use of medical cannabis to try to increase appetite or weight gain.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS has become a chronic rather than an acutely fatal disease in many areas of the world.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Prognosis varies between people, and both the CD4 count and viral load are useful for predicted outcomes.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Without treatment, average survival time after infection with HIV is estimated to be 9 to 11 years, depending on the HIV subtype.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] After the diagnosis of AIDS, if treatment is not available, survival ranges between 6 and 19 months.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] ART and appropriate prevention of opportunistic infections reduces the death rate by 80%, and raises the life expectancy for a newly diagnosed young adult to 20–50 years.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This is between two thirds and nearly that of the general population.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] If treatment is started late in the infection, prognosis is not as good: for example, if treatment is begun following the diagnosis of AIDS, life expectancy is ~10–40 years.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Half of infants born with HIV die before two years of age without treatment.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The primary causes of death from HIV/AIDS are opportunistic infections and cancer, both of which are frequently the result of the progressive failure of the immune system.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Risk of cancer appears to increase once the CD4 count is below 500/μL.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Tuberculosis co-infection is one of the leading causes of sickness and death in those with HIV/AIDS being present in a third of all HIV-infected people and causing 25% of HIV-related deaths.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV is also one of the most important risk factors for tuberculosis.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Hepatitis C is another very common co-infection where each disease increases the progression of the other.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The two most common cancers associated with HIV/AIDS are Kaposi's sarcoma and AIDS-related non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Other cancers that are more frequent include anal cancer, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Even with anti-retroviral treatment, over the long term HIV-infected people may experience neurocognitive disorders, osteoporosis, neuropathy, cancers, nephropathy, and cardiovascular disease.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Some conditions, such as lipodystrophy, may be caused both by HIV and its treatment.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a global pandemic.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] As of 2025, approximately 40.9 million people worldwide are living with HIV, the number of new infections that year being about 1.2 million.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This is down 43% from 2.1 million new infections in 2010.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Among new infections, 41% are in women and girls globally.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There were [CONFIRM 2025 figure] AIDS-related deaths in 2025, down from a peak of 2 million in 2005.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Among persons living with HIV (PLWH), the largest proportion reside in eastern and southern Africa (20.6 million, 54.6%).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] This region also had the highest rate of adult and child deaths due to AIDS in 2020 (310,000, 46.6%).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Sub-Saharan African adolescent girls and young women (aged 15–24 years) account for 77% of new infections among this age-range globally.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Here, in contrast to other regions, adolescent girls and young women are three times more likely to acquire HIV than age-matched males.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Despite these statistics, overall, new HIV infections and AIDS-related deaths have substantially decreased in this region since 2010.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Eastern Europe and central Asia has observed a 43% increase in new HIV infections and 32% increase in AIDS-related deaths since 2010, the highest of all global regions.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] These infections are predominantly distributed in persons who inject drugs, with gay men and other men who have sex with men or persons who engage in transaction sex the second and third populations most impacted in this region.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] At the end of 2019, United States indicated that approximately 1.2 million people aged ≥13 years were living with HIV, resulting in about 18,500 deaths in 2020.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] There were 34,800 estimated new infections in the US in 2019, 53% of which were in the southern region of the country.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In addition to geographic location, significant disparities in HIV incidence exist among men, Black or Hispanic populations, and men who reported male-to-male sexual contact.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimated that in that year, 158,500 people or 13% of infected Americans were unaware of their infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In the United Kingdom as of 2015, there were approximately 101,200 cases which resulted in 594 deaths.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] In Canada as of 2008, there were about 65,000 cases causing 53 deaths.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Between the first recognition of AIDS (in 1981) and 2009, it has led to nearly 30 million deaths.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Rates of HIV are lowest in North Africa and the Middle East (0.1% or less), East Asia (0.1%), and Western and Central Europe (0.2%).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] The worst-affected European countries, in 2009 and 2012 estimates, are Russia, Ukraine, Latvia, Moldova, Portugal and Belarus, in decreasing order of prevalence.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Groups at higher risk of acquiring HIV include persons who engage in transactional sex, gay men and other men who have sex with men, persons who inject drugs, transgender persons, and those who are incarcerated or detained.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p01] Climate change impacts HIV risk and the availability of and access to HIV prevention and treatment services, and can contribute to poor nutrition, impaired immunity, and poor adherence to treatment.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The first news story on the disease appeared on May 18, 1981, in the gay newspaper *New York Native*.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] AIDS was first clinically reported on June 5, 1981, with five cases in the United States.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The initial cases were a cluster of injecting drug users and gay men with no known cause of impaired immunity who showed symptoms of *Pneumocystis carinii* pneumonia (PCP), a rare opportunistic infection that was known to occur in people with very compromised immune systems.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Soon thereafter, a large number of homosexual men developed a generally rare skin cancer called Kaposi's sarcoma (KS).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Many more cases of PCP and KS emerged, alerting the U.S.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and a CDC task force was formed to monitor the outbreak.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In the early days, the CDC did not have an official name for the disease, often referring to it by way of diseases associated with it, such as lymphadenopathy, the disease after which the discoverers of HIV originally named the virus.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] They also used *Kaposi's sarcoma and opportunistic infections*, the name by which a task force had been set up in 1981.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] At one point the CDC referred to it as the "4H disease", as the syndrome seemed to affect heroin users, homosexuals, hemophiliacs, and Haitians.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The term *GRID*, which stood for gay-related immune deficiency, had also been coined.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] However, after determining that AIDS was not isolated to the gay community, it was realized that the term *GRID* was misleading, and the term *AIDS* was introduced at a meeting in July 1982.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] By September 1982 the CDC started referring to the disease as AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In 1983, two separate research groups led by Robert Gallo and Luc Montagnier declared that a novel retrovirus may have been infecting people with AIDS, and published their findings in the same issue of the journal *Science*.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Gallo claimed a virus which his group had isolated from a person with AIDS was strikingly similar in shape to other human T-lymphotropic viruses (HTLVs) that his group had been the first to isolate.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Gallo's group called their newly isolated virus HTLV-III.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] At the same time, Montagnier's group isolated a virus from a person presenting with swelling of the lymph nodes of the neck and physical weakness, two characteristic symptoms of AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Contradicting the report from Gallo's group, Montagnier and his colleagues showed that core proteins of this virus were immunologically different from those of HTLV-I.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Montagnier's group named their isolated virus lymphadenopathy-associated virus (LAV).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] As these two viruses turned out to be the same, in 1986, LAV and HTLV-III were renamed HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The origin of HIV / AIDS and the circumstances that led to its emergence remain unsolved.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Both HIV-1 and HIV-2 are believed to have originated in non-human primates in West-central Africa and were transferred to humans in the early 20th century.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] HIV-1 appears to have originated in southern Cameroon through the evolution of SIV(cpz), a simian immunodeficiency virus (SIV) that infects wild chimpanzees (HIV-1 descends from the SIVcpz endemic in the chimpanzee subspecies *Pan troglodytes troglodytes*).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The closest relative of HIV-2 is SIV (smm), a virus of the sooty mangabey (*Cercocebus atys atys*), an Old World monkey living in coastal West Africa (from southern Senegal to western Ivory Coast).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] New World monkeys such as the owl monkey are resistant to HIV-1 infection, possibly because of a genomic fusion of two viral resistance genes.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] HIV-1 is thought to have jumped the species barrier on at least three separate occasions, giving rise to the three groups of the virus, M, N, and O.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] There is evidence that humans who participate in bushmeat activities, either as hunters or as bushmeat vendors, commonly acquire SIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] However, SIV is a weak virus which is typically suppressed by the human immune system within weeks of infection.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] It is thought that several transmissions of the virus from individual to individual in quick succession are necessary to allow it enough time to mutate into HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Furthermore, due to its relatively low person-to-person transmission rate, SIV can only spread throughout the population in the presence of one or more high-risk transmission channels, which are thought to have been absent in Africa before the 20th century.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Specific proposed high-risk transmission channels, allowing the virus to adapt to humans and spread throughout society, depend on the proposed timing of the animal-to-human crossing.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Genetic studies of the virus suggest that the most recent common ancestor of the HIV-1 M group dates back to c.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] While transmission rates of HIV during vaginal intercourse are low under regular circumstances, they are increased manyfold if one of the partners has a sexually transmitted infection causing genital ulcers.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] An alternative view holds that unsafe medical practices in Africa after World War II, such as unsterile reuse of single-use syringes during mass vaccination, antibiotic and anti-malaria treatment campaigns, were the initial vector that allowed the virus to adapt to humans and spread.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The earliest well-documented case of HIV in a human dates back to 1959 in the Congo.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The virus may have been present in the U.S. as early as the mid-to-late 1950s.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] A 16-year-old male named Robert Rayford presented with symptoms in 1966 and died in 1969.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In the 1970s, there were cases of people getting parasites and becoming sick with what was then called "gay bowel disease" but is now suspected to have been AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The earliest retrospectively described case of AIDS is believed to have been in Norway beginning in 1966, that of Arvid Noe.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In July 1960, in the wake of Congo's independence, the United Nations recruited Francophone experts and technicians from all over the world to assist in filling administrative gaps left by Belgium, who did not leave behind an African elite to run the country.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] By 1962, Haitians made up the second-largest group of well-educated experts (out of the 48 national groups recruited), that totaled around 4,500 in the country.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Jacques Pépin, a Canadian author of *The Origins of AIDS*, stipulates that Haiti was one of HIV's entry points to the U.S. and that a Haitian may have carried HIV back across the Atlantic in the 1960s.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The epidemic rapidly spread among high-risk groups (initially, sexually promiscuous men who have sex with men).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] By 1978, the prevalence of HIV-1 among gay male residents of New York City and San Francisco was estimated at 5%, suggesting that several thousand individuals in the country had been infected.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Stigma-related violence or the fear of violence prevents many people from seeking HIV testing, returning for their results, or securing treatment, possibly turning what could be a manageable chronic illness into a death sentence and perpetuating the spread of HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Often, AIDS stigma is expressed in conjunction with one or more other stigmas, particularly those associated with homosexuality, bisexuality, promiscuity, prostitution, and intravenous drug use.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In many developed countries, there is an association between AIDS and homosexuality or bisexuality, and this association is correlated with higher levels of sexual prejudice, such as anti-homosexual or anti-bisexual attitudes.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] There is also a perceived association between AIDS and all male-male sexual behavior, including sex between uninfected men.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] However, the dominant mode of spread worldwide for HIV remains heterosexual transmission.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The NAMES Project AIDS Memorial Quilt was conceived in 1985 to celebrate the lives of those who had died of AIDS when stigma prevented many from receiving funerals.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] It is now cared for by the National AIDS Memorial in San Francisco.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In 2003, as part of an overall reform of marriage and population legislation, it became legal for those diagnosed with AIDS to marry in China.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Between 2004 and 2020, Somen Debnath has travelled the world by bicycle promoting HIV / AIDS awareness.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] National Library of Medicine developed a traveling exhibition titled *Surviving and Thriving: AIDS, Politics, and Culture*; this covered medical research, the U.S. government's response, and personal stories from people with AIDS, caregivers, and activists.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Stigma has proved an obstacle to the update of PrEP.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Within the MSM community, the greatest barrier to PrEP use has been the stigma surrounding HIV and gay men.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Gay men on PrEP have experienced "slut-shaming".
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Numerous other barriers have been identified, including lack of quality LGBTQ care, cost, and adherence to medication use.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] HIV/AIDS affects the economics of both individuals and countries.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The gross domestic product of the most affected countries has decreased due to the lack of human capital.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Without proper nutrition, health care and medicine, large numbers of people die from AIDS-related complications.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Before death they will not only be unable to work, but will also require significant medical care.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] It is estimated that as of 2007 there were 12 million AIDS orphans.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Many are cared for by elderly grandparents.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Returning to work after beginning treatment for HIV/AIDS is difficult, and affected people often work less than the average worker.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Unemployment in people with HIV/AIDS also is associated with suicidal ideation, memory problems, and social isolation.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Employment increases self-esteem, sense of dignity, confidence, and quality of life for people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Anti-retroviral treatment may help people with HIV/AIDS work more, and may increase the chance that a person with HIV/AIDS will be employed (low-quality evidence).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] By affecting mainly young adults, AIDS reduces the taxable population, in turn reducing the resources available for public expenditures such as education and health services not related to AIDS, resulting in increasing pressure on the state's finances and slower growth of the economy.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] This causes a slower growth of the tax base, an effect that is reinforced if there are growing expenditures on treating the sick, training (to replace sick workers), sick pay, and caring for AIDS orphans.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] This is especially true if the sharp increase in adult mortality shifts the responsibility from the family to the government in caring for these orphans.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] At the household level, AIDS causes both loss of income and increased spending on healthcare.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] A study in Côte d'Ivoire showed that households having a person with HIV/AIDS spent twice as much on medical expenses as other households.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] This additional expenditure also leaves less income to spend on education and other personal or family investment.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The topic of religion and AIDS has become highly controversial, primarily because some religious authorities have publicly declared their opposition to the use of condoms.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Some religious organizations have claimed that prayer can cure HIV/AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In 2011, the BBC reported that some churches in London were claiming that prayer would cure AIDS, and the Hackney-based Centre for the Study of Sexual Health and HIV reported that several people stopped taking their medication, sometimes on the direct advice of their pastor, leading to many deaths.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] The Synagogue Church Of All Nations advertised an "anointing water" to promote God's healing, although the group denies advising people to stop taking medication.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] One of the first high-profile cases of AIDS was the American gay actor Rock Hudson.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] He had been diagnosed during 1984, announced that he had had the virus on July 25, 1985, and died a few months later on October 2, 1985.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Another notable British casualty of AIDS that year was Nicholas Eden, a gay politician and son of former prime minister Anthony Eden.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] On November 24, 1991, British rock star Freddie Mercury died from an AIDS-related illness, having revealed the diagnosis only on the previous day.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] One of the first high-profile heterosexual cases of the virus was American tennis player Arthur Ashe.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] He was diagnosed as HIV-positive on August 31, 1988, having contracted the virus from blood transfusions during heart surgery earlier in the 1980s.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Further tests within 24 hours of the initial diagnosis revealed that Ashe had AIDS, but he did not tell the public about his diagnosis until April 1992.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] He died as a result on February 6, 1993, aged 49.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Therese Frare's photograph of gay activist David Kirby, as he lay dying from AIDS while surrounded by family, was taken in April 1990.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] *Life* magazine said the photo became the one image "most powerfully identified with the HIV/AIDS epidemic." The photo was displayed in *Life*, was the winner of the World Press Photo, and acquired worldwide notoriety after being used in a United Colors of Benetton advertising campaign in 1992.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Many famous artists and AIDS activists such as Larry Kramer, Diamanda Galás and Rosa von Praunheim campaign for AIDS education and the rights of those affected.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] These artists worked with various media formats.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Criminal transmission of HIV is the intentional or reckless infection of a person with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Some countries or jurisdictions, including some areas of the United States, have laws that criminalize HIV transmission or exposure.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Others may charge the accused under laws enacted before the HIV pandemic.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In 1996, Ugandan-born Canadian Johnson Aziga was diagnosed with HIV; he subsequently had unprotected sex with eleven women without disclosing his diagnosis.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] By 2003, seven had contracted HIV; two died from complications related to AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Aziga was convicted of first-degree murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] There are many misconceptions about HIV and AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Three misconceptions are that AIDS can spread through casual contact, that sexual intercourse with a virgin will cure AIDS, and that HIV can infect only gay men and drug users.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] In 2014, some among the British public wrongly thought one could get HIV from kissing (16%), sharing a glass (5%), spitting (16%), a public toilet seat (4%), and coughing or sneezing (5%).
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Other misconceptions are that any act of anal intercourse between two uninfected gay men can lead to HIV infection, and that open discussion of HIV and homosexuality in schools will lead to increased rates of AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] A small group of individuals continue to dispute the connection between HIV and AIDS, the existence of HIV itself, or the validity of HIV testing and treatment methods.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] These claims, known as AIDS denialism, have been examined and rejected by the scientific community.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Several discredited conspiracy theories have held that HIV was created by scientists, either inadvertently or deliberately.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Operation INFEKTION was a worldwide Soviet active measures operation to spread the claim that the United States had created HIV/AIDS.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Surveys show that a significant number of people believed—and continue to believe—in such claims.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] HIV/AIDS research includes all medical research which attempts to prevent, treat, or cure HIV/AIDS, along with fundamental research about the nature of HIV as an infectious agent, and about AIDS as the disease caused by HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Many governments and research institutions participate in HIV/AIDS research.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] This research includes behavioral health interventions such as sex education, and drug development, such as research into microbicides for sexually transmitted diseases, HIV vaccines, and antiretroviral drugs.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Other medical research areas include the topics of pre-exposure prophylaxis, post-exposure prophylaxis, and circumcision and HIV.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Public health officials, researchers, and programs can gain a more comprehensive picture of the barriers they face, and the efficacy of current approaches to HIV treatment and prevention, by tracking standard HIV indicators.
[src:ascomycota/aids-p02] Use of common indicators is an increasing focus of development organizations and researchers.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The **Ascomycota** are a phylum in the kingdom Fungi that, together with the Basidiomycota, form the subkingdom Dikarya.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Members of Ascomycota are commonly known as the **sac fungi** or **ascomycetes**.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] It is the largest phylum of Fungi, with over 64,000 species.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The defining feature of this fungal group is the *ascus* (from Ancient Greek ἀσκός*(*askós*)* 'sac, wineskin'), a microscopic sexual structure in which nonmotile spores, called ascospores, are formed.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] However, some species of Ascomycota are asexual and thus do not form asci or ascospores.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Familiar examples of sac fungi include morels, truffles, brewers' and bakers' yeast, dead man's fingers, and cup fungi.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The fungal symbionts in the majority of lichens (loosely termed "ascolichens") such as *Cladonia* belong to the Ascomycota.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Ascomycota are a monophyletic group (containing all of the descendants of a common ancestor).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Previously placed in the Basidiomycota along with asexual species from other fungal taxa, asexual (or anamorphic) ascomycetes are now identified and classified based on morphological or physiological similarities to ascus-bearing taxa, and by phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Ascomycetes are of particular use to humans as sources of medicinally important compounds such as antibiotics, as well as for fermenting bread, alcoholic beverages, and cheese.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Examples of ascomycetes include *Penicillium* species on cheeses and those producing antibiotics for treating bacterial infectious diseases.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Many ascomycetes are pathogens, both of animals, including humans, and of plants.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Examples of ascomycetes that can cause infections in humans include *Candida albicans*, *Aspergillus niger* and several tens of species that cause skin infections.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The many plant-pathogenic ascomycetes include apple scab, rice blast, the ergot fungi, black knot, and the powdery mildews.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The members of the genus *Cordyceps* are entomopathogenic fungi, meaning that they parasitise and kill insects.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Other entomopathogenic ascomycetes have been used successfully in biological pest control, such as *Beauveria*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Several species of ascomycetes are biological model organisms in laboratory research.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Most famously, *Neurospora crassa*, several species of yeasts, and *Aspergillus* species are used in many genetics and cell biology studies.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] They are fungi which produce microscopic spores inside special, elongated cells or sacs, known as *asci*, which give the group its name.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Asexual reproduction is the dominant form of propagation in the Ascomycota, and is responsible for the rapid spread of these fungi into new areas.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Asexual reproduction of ascomycetes is very diverse from both structural and functional points of view.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The most important and general is production of conidia, but chlamydospores are also frequently produced.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Furthermore, Ascomycota also reproduce asexually through budding.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Asexual reproduction may occur through vegetative reproductive spores, the conidia.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The asexual, non-motile haploid spores of a fungus, which are named after the Greek word for dust (conia), are hence also known as *conidiospores*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The conidiospores commonly contain one nucleus and are products of mitotic cell divisions and thus are sometimes called *mitospores*, which are genetically identical to the mycelium from which they originate.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] They are typically formed at the ends of specialized hyphae, the conidiophores.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Depending on the species they may be dispersed by wind or water, or by animals.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Conidiophores may simply branch off from the mycelia or they may be formed in fruiting bodies.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The hypha that creates the sporing (conidiating) tip can be very similar to the normal hyphal tip, or it can be differentiated.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The most common differentiation is the formation of a bottle shaped cell called a *phialide*, from which the spores are produced.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Not all of these asexual structures are a single hypha.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In some groups, the conidiophores (the structures that bear the conidia) are aggregated to form a thick structure.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In the order *Moniliales,* all of them are single hyphae with the exception of the aggregations, termed as coremia or synnema.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] These produce structures rather like corn-stokes, with many conidia being produced in a mass from the aggregated conidiophores.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The diverse conidia and conidiophores sometimes develop in asexual sporocarps with different characteristics (e.g. acervulus, pycnidium, sporodochium).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Some species of ascomycetes form their structures within plant tissue, either as parasite or saprophytes.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] These fungi have evolved more complex asexual sporing structures, probably influenced by the cultural conditions of plant tissue as a substrate.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] These structures are called the *sporodochium*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] This is a cushion of conidiophores created from a pseudoparenchymatous stroma in plant tissue.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The *pycnidium* is a globose to flask-shaped parenchymatous structure, lined on its inner wall with conidiophores.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The *acervulus* is a flat saucer shaped bed of conidiophores produced under a plant cuticle, which eventually erupt through the cuticle for dispersal.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Asexual reproduction process in ascomycetes also involves the budding which we clearly observe in yeast.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] It involves the blowing out or blebbing of the hyphal tip wall.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The blastic process can involve all wall layers, or there can be a new cell wall synthesized which is extruded from within the old wall.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The initial events of budding can be seen as the development of a ring of chitin around the point where the bud is about to appear.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] This reinforces and stabilizes the cell wall.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Enzymatic activity and turgor pressure act to weaken and extrude the cell wall.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] New cell wall material is incorporated during this phase.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Cell contents are forced into the progeny cell, and as the final phase of mitosis ends a cell plate, the point at which a new cell wall will grow inwards from, forms.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Several outdated taxon names—based on morphological features—are still occasionally used for species of the Ascomycota.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Hemiascomycetes included the yeasts and yeast-like fungi that have now been placed into the Saccharomycotina or Taphrinomycotina, while the Euascomycetes included the remaining species of the Ascomycota, which are now in the Pezizomycotina, and the Neolecta, which are in the Taphrinomycotina.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Some ascomycetes do not reproduce sexually or are not known to produce asci and are therefore anamorphic species.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Those anamorphs that produce conidia (mitospores) were previously described as mitosporic Ascomycota.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Some taxonomists placed this group into a separate artificial phylum, the Deuteromycota (or "Fungi Imperfecti").
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Where recent molecular analyses have identified close relationships with ascus-bearing taxa, anamorphic species have been grouped into the Ascomycota, despite the absence of the defining ascus.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Sexual and asexual isolates of the same species commonly carry different binomial species names, as, for example, *Aspergillus nidulans* and *Emericella nidulans*, for asexual and sexual isolates, respectively, of the same species.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Species of the Deuteromycota were classified as Coelomycetes if they produced their conidia in minute flask- or saucer-shaped conidiomata, known technically as *pycnidia* and *acervuli*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The Hyphomycetes were those species where the conidiophores (*i.e.*, the hyphal structures that carry conidia-forming cells at the end) are free or loosely organized.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] They are mostly isolated but sometimes also appear as bundles of cells aligned in parallel (described as *synnematal*) or as cushion-shaped masses (described as *sporodochial*).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Most species grow as filamentous, microscopic structures called hyphae or as budding single cells (yeasts).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Many interconnected hyphae form a thallus usually referred to as the mycelium, which—when visible to the naked eye (macroscopic)—is commonly called mold.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] During sexual reproduction, many Ascomycota typically produce large numbers of asci.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The ascus is often contained in a multicellular, occasionally readily visible fruiting structure, the ascocarp (also called an *ascoma*).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Their texture can likewise be very variable, including fleshy, like charcoal (carbonaceous), leathery, rubbery, gelatinous, slimy, powdery, or cob-web-like.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Ascocarps come in multiple colors such as red, orange, yellow, brown, black, or, more rarely, green or blue.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Some ascomyceous fungi, such as *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, grow as single-celled yeasts, which—during sexual reproduction—develop into an ascus, and do not form fruiting bodies.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In lichenized species, the thallus of the fungus defines the shape of the symbiotic colony.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Some dimorphic species, such as *Candida albicans*, can switch between growth as single cells and as filamentous, multicellular hyphae.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Other species are pleomorphic, exhibiting asexual (anamorphic) as well as a sexual (teleomorphic) growth forms.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Except for lichens, the non-reproductive (vegetative) mycelium of most ascomycetes is usually inconspicuous because it is commonly embedded in the substrate, such as soil, or grows on or inside a living host, and only the ascoma may be seen when fruiting.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Pigmentation, such as melanin in hyphal walls, along with prolific growth on surfaces can result in visible mold colonies; examples include *Cladosporium* species, which form black spots on bathroom caulking and other moist areas.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Many ascomycetes cause food spoilage, and, therefore, the pellicles or moldy layers that develop on jams, juices, and other foods are the mycelia of these species or occasionally Mucoromycotina and almost never Basidiomycota.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Sooty molds that develop on plants, especially in the tropics are the thalli of many species.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Large masses of yeast cells, asci or ascus-like cells, or conidia can also form macroscopic structures.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] *Pneumocystis* species can colonize lung cavities (visible in x-rays), causing a form of pneumonia.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Asci of *Ascosphaera* fill honey bee larvae and pupae causing mummification with a chalk-like appearance, hence the name "chalkbrood".
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Yeasts for small colonies in vitro and in vivo, and excessive growth of *Candida* species in the mouth or vagina causes "thrush", a form of candidiasis.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The cell walls of the ascomycetes almost always contain chitin and β-glucans, and divisions within the hyphae, called "septa", are the internal boundaries of individual cells (or compartments).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The cell wall and septa give stability and rigidity to the hyphae and may prevent loss of cytoplasm in case of local damage to cell wall and cell membrane.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The septa commonly have a small opening in the center, which functions as a cytoplasmic connection between adjacent cells, also sometimes allowing cell-to-cell movement of nuclei within a hypha.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Vegetative hyphae of most ascomycetes contain only one nucleus per cell (*uninucleate* hyphae), but multinucleate cells—especially in the apical regions of growing hyphae—can also be present.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In common with other fungal phyla, the Ascomycota are heterotrophic organisms that require organic compounds as energy sources.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] These are obtained by feeding on a variety of organic substrates including dead matter, foodstuffs, or as symbionts in or on other living organisms.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] To obtain these nutrients from their surroundings, ascomycetous fungi secrete powerful digestive enzymes that break down organic substances into smaller molecules, which are then taken up into the cell.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Many species live on dead plant material such as leaves, twigs, or logs.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Several species colonize plants, animals, or other fungi as parasites or mutualistic symbionts and derive all their metabolic energy in form of nutrients from the tissues of their hosts.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Owing to their long evolutionary history, the Ascomycota have evolved the capacity to break down almost every organic substance.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Unlike most organisms, they are able to use their own enzymes to digest plant biopolymers such as cellulose or lignin.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Collagen, an abundant structural protein in animals, and keratin—a protein that forms hair and nails—, can also serve as food sources.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Unusual examples include *Aureobasidium pullulans*, which feeds on wall paint, and the kerosene fungus *Amorphotheca resinae*, which feeds on aircraft fuel (causing occasional problems for the airline industry), and may sometimes block fuel pipes.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Other species can resist high osmotic stress and grow, for example, on salted fish, and a few ascomycetes are aquatic.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The Ascomycota is characterized by a high degree of specialization; for instance, certain species of Laboulbeniales attack only one particular leg of one particular insect species.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Many Ascomycota engage in symbiotic relationships such as in lichens—symbiotic associations with green algae or cyanobacteria—in which the fungal symbiont directly obtains products of photosynthesis.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In common with many basidiomycetes and Glomeromycota, some ascomycetes form symbioses with plants by colonizing the roots to form mycorrhizal associations.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The Ascomycota also represents several carnivorous fungi, which have developed hyphal traps to capture small protists such as amoebae, as well as roundworms (*Nematoda*), rotifers, tardigrades, and small arthropods such as springtails (*Collembola*).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The Ascomycota are represented in all land ecosystems worldwide, occurring on all continents including Antarctica.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Spores and hyphal fragments are dispersed through the atmosphere and freshwater environments, as well as ocean beaches and tidal zones.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The distribution of species is variable; while some are found on all continents, others, as for example the white truffle *Tuber magnatum*, only occur in isolated locations in Italy and Eastern Europe.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The distribution of plant-parasitic species is often restricted by host distributions; for example, *Cyttaria* is only found on *Nothofagus* (Southern Beech) in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] It occurs through vegetative reproductive spores, the conidia.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The conidiospores commonly contain one nucleus and are products of mitotic cell divisions and thus are sometimes called mitospores, which are genetically identical to the mycelium from which they originate.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] They are typically formed at the ends of specialized hyphae, the *conidiophores*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Different types of asexual spores can be identified by colour, shape, and how they are released as individual spores.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Spore types can be used as taxonomic characters in the classification within the Ascomycota.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The most frequent types are the single-celled spores, which are designated *amerospores*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] If the spore is divided into two by a cross-wall (septum), it is called a *didymospore*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] When there are two or more cross-walls, the classification depends on spore shape.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] If the septae are *transversal*, like the rungs of a ladder, it is a *phragmospore*, and if they possess a net-like structure it is a *dictyospore*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In *staurospores* ray-like arms radiate from a central body; in others (*helicospores*) the entire spore is wound up in a spiral like a spring.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Very long worm-like spores with a length-to-diameter ratio of more than 15:1, are called *scolecospores*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Important characteristics of the anamorphs of the Ascomycota are *conidiogenesis*, which includes spore formation and dehiscence (separation from the parent structure).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The spores may or may not be generated in a large-scale specialized structure that helps to spread them.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Sometimes the conidia are produced in structures visible to the naked eye, which help to distribute the spores.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] These structures are called "conidiomata" (singular: conidioma), and may take the form of *pycnidia* (which are flask-shaped and arise in the fungal tissue) or *acervuli* (which are cushion-shaped and arise in host tissue).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In *schizolytic* dehiscence, a double-dividing wall with a central lamella (layer) forms between the cells; the central layer then breaks down thereby releasing the spores.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In *rhexolytic* dehiscence, the cell wall that joins the spores on the outside degenerates and releases the conidia.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Several Ascomycota species are not known to have a sexual cycle.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Such asexual species may be able to undergo genetic recombination between individuals by processes involving *heterokaryosis* and *parasexual* events.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Parasexuality refers to the process of heterokaryosis, caused by merging of two hyphae belonging to different individuals, by a process called *anastomosis*, followed by a series of events resulting in genetically different cell nuclei in the mycelium.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The merging of nuclei is not followed by meiotic events, such as gamete formation and results in an increased number of chromosomes per nuclei.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] *Mitotic crossover* may enable recombination, i.e., an exchange of genetic material between homologous chromosomes.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The chromosome number may then be restored to its haploid state by nuclear division, with each daughter nuclei being genetically different from the original parent nuclei.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Alternatively, nuclei may lose some chromosomes, resulting in aneuploid cells.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] *Candida albicans* (class Saccharomycetes) is an example of a fungus that has a parasexual cycle (see Candida albicans and Parasexual cycle).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Sexual reproduction in the Ascomycota leads to the formation of the *ascus*, the structure that defines this fungal group and distinguishes it from other fungal phyla.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The ascus is a tube-shaped vessel, a *meiosporangium*, which contains the sexual spores produced by meiosis and which are called *ascospores*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Apart from a few exceptions, such as *Candida albicans*, most ascomycetes are haploid, i.e., they contain one set of chromosomes per nucleus.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] During sexual reproduction there is a diploid phase, which commonly is very short, and meiosis restores the haploid state.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The sexual cycle of one well-studied representative species of Ascomycota is described in greater detail in *Neurospora crassa*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Also, the adaptive basis for the maintenance of sexual reproduction in the Ascomycota fungi was reviewed by Wallen and Perlin.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] They concluded that the most plausible reason for the maintenance of this capability is the benefit of repairing DNA damage by using recombination that occurs during meiosis.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] DNA damage can be caused by a variety of stresses such as nutrient limitation.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The sexual part of the life cycle commences when two hyphal structures mate.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In the case of *homothallic* species, mating is enabled between hyphae of the same fungal clone, whereas in *heterothallic* species, the two hyphae must originate from fungal clones that differ genetically, i.e., those that are of a different mating type.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Mating types are typical of the fungi and correspond roughly to the sexes in plants and animals; however one species may have more than two mating types, resulting in sometimes complex vegetative incompatibility systems.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The adaptive function of mating type is discussed in *Neurospora crassa*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Gametangia are sexual structures formed from hyphae, and are the generative cells.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] A very fine hypha, called trichogyne emerges from one gametangium, the *ascogonium*, and merges with a gametangium (the *antheridium*) of the other fungal isolate.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The nuclei in the antheridium then migrate into the ascogonium, and plasmogamy—the mixing of the cytoplasm—occurs.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Unlike in animals and plants, plasmogamy is not immediately followed by the merging of the nuclei (called *karyogamy*).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Instead, the nuclei from the two hyphae form pairs, initiating the *dikaryophase* of the sexual cycle, during which time the pairs of nuclei synchronously divide.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Fusion of the paired nuclei leads to mixing of the genetic material and recombination and is followed by meiosis.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] A similar sexual cycle is present in the red algae (Rhodophyta).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] From the fertilized ascogonium, *dinucleate* hyphae emerge in which each cell contains two nuclei.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] These hyphae are called *ascogenous* or fertile hyphae.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] They are supported by the vegetative mycelium containing uni– (or mono–) nucleate hyphae, which are sterile.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The mycelium containing both sterile and fertile hyphae may grow into fruiting body, the *ascocarp*, which may contain millions of fertile hyphae.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] An ascocarp is the fruiting body of the sexual phase in Ascomycota.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The sexual structures are formed in the fruiting layer of the ascocarp, the hymenium.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] At one end of ascogenous hyphae, characteristic U-shaped hooks develop, which curve back opposite to the growth direction of the hyphae.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The two nuclei contained in the apical part of each hypha divide in such a way that the threads of their mitotic spindles run parallel, creating two pairs of genetically different nuclei.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] One daughter nucleus migrates close to the hook, while the other daughter nucleus locates to the basal part of the hypha.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The formation of two parallel cross-walls then divides the hypha into three sections: one at the hook with one nucleus, one at the basal of the original hypha that contains one nucleus, and one that separates the U-shaped part, which contains the other two nuclei.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Fusion of the nuclei (karyogamy) takes place in the U-shaped cells in the hymenium, and results in the formation of a diploid zygote.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The zygote grows into the ascus, an elongated tube-shaped or cylinder-shaped capsule.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Meiosis then gives rise to four haploid nuclei, usually followed by a further mitotic division that results in eight nuclei in each ascus.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The nuclei along with some cytoplasma become enclosed within membranes and a cell wall to give rise to ascospores that are aligned inside the ascus like peas in a pod.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Upon opening of the ascus, ascospores may be dispersed by the wind, while in some cases the spores are forcibly ejected form the ascus; certain species have evolved spore cannons, which can eject ascospores up to 30 cm. away.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] When the spores reach a suitable substrate, they germinate, form new hyphae, which restarts the fungal life cycle.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The form of the ascus is important for classification and is divided into four basic types: unitunicate-operculate, unitunicate-inoperculate, bitunicate, or prototunicate.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] See the article on asci for further details.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The Ascomycota fulfil a central role in most land-based ecosystems.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] They are important decomposers, breaking down organic materials, such as dead leaves and animals, and helping the detritivores (animals that feed on decomposing material) to obtain their nutrients.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Ascomycetes, along with other fungi, can break down large molecules such as cellulose or lignin, and thus have important roles in nutrient cycling such as the carbon cycle.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The fruiting bodies of the Ascomycota provide food for many animals ranging from insects and slugs and snails (*Gastropoda*) to rodents and larger mammals such as deer and wild boars.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Many ascomycetes also form symbiotic relationships with other organisms, including plants and animals.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Probably since early in their evolutionary history, the Ascomycota have formed symbiotic associations with green algae (*Chlorophyta*), and other types of algae and cyanobacteria.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] These mutualistic associations are commonly known as lichens, and can grow and persist in terrestrial regions of the earth that are inhospitable to other organisms and characterized by extremes in temperature and humidity, including the Arctic, the Antarctic, deserts, and mountaintops.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] While the photoautotrophic algal partner generates metabolic energy through photosynthesis, the fungus offers a stable, supportive matrix and protects cells from radiation and dehydration.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Around 42% of the Ascomycota (about 18,000 species) form lichens, and almost all the fungal partners of lichens belong to the Ascomycota.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Members of the Ascomycota form two important types of relationship with plants: as mycorrhizal fungi and as endophytes.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Mycorrhiza are symbiotic associations of fungi with the root systems of the plants, which can be of vital importance for growth and persistence for the plant.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The fine mycelial network of the fungus enables the increased uptake of mineral salts that occur at low levels in the soil.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] In return, the plant provides the fungus with metabolic energy in the form of photosynthetic products.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Endophytic fungi live inside plants, and those that form mutualistic or commensal associations with their host, do not damage their hosts.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Several ascomycetes of the genus *Xylaria* colonize the nests of leafcutter ants and other fungus-growing ants of the tribe Attini, and the fungal gardens of termites (Isoptera).
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Since they do not generate fruiting bodies until the insects have left the nests, it is suspected that, as confirmed in several cases of Basidiomycota species, they may be cultivated.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Bark beetles (family Scolytidae) are important symbiotic partners of ascomycetes.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The female beetles transport fungal spores to new hosts in characteristic tucks in their skin, the *mycetangia*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The beetle tunnels into the wood and into large chambers in which they lay their eggs.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] Spores released from the mycetangia germinate into hyphae, which can break down the wood.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] The beetle larvae then feed on the fungal mycelium, and, on reaching maturity, carry new spores with them to renew the cycle of infection.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] A well-known example of this is Dutch elm disease, caused by *Ophiostoma ulmi*, which is carried by the European elm bark beetle, *Scolytus multistriatus*.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] One of their most harmful roles is as the agent of many plant diseases.
[src:ascomycota/ascomycota] On the other hand, ascus fungi have brought some significant benefits to humanity.
